{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb2c3688-223d-4cd4-bbc0-ee67dadd15b7","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project and code are fine — the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation**, which happens on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server in memory.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop**\nKeeps the host process alive and rebuilds on file changes — eliminates repeated startup cost entirely.\n\n**2. Skip restore on incremental builds**\n```\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nThe implicit `dotnet restore` adds ~500ms+ even when all packages are already resolved. Run restore once, then use `--no-restore` for subsequent builds.\n\n**3. Enable the MSBuild Build Server**\nSet the environment variable to reuse a long-lived MSBuild server process between CLI invocations (the same technique VS uses):\n```\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nOr add to the `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nThis keeps the Roslyn VBCSCompiler server alive between builds, avoiding compiler JIT overhead.\n\n**4. Use Terminal Logger for faster perceived builds**\n```\ndotnet build -tl\n```\nReduces console output overhead and gives clearer timing info.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The `.csproj` itself has no misconfigurations. The slowness is inherent to cold-starting MSBuild on every CLI invocation. `dotnet watch build` is the single biggest win for edit-build-test cycles; `--no-restore` and the MSBuild server close most of the remaining gap with VS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c44947b7-9bc1-4809-a9c0-669399aecc41","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds), even when nothing has changed. Visual Studio builds are nearly instant. They've verified analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets are working.\n\nThe key insight here is about the difference between how Visual Studio and the CLI handle MSBuild:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** uses a long-lived MSBuild server process that keeps the project graph loaded in memory. When you rebuild, it doesn't need to re-parse project files, resolve SDKs, or JIT the MSBuild engine.\n\n2. **dotnet build** (CLI) by default spawns a new MSBuild process each time, which means:\n   - .NET runtime startup and JIT compilation\n   - SDK resolution\n   - Project file parsing and evaluation\n   - NuGet restore checks\n   - Target graph evaluation\n\nThe main solutions are enabling the MSBuild server (available in .NET 8+ via `-tl` flag or environment variables like `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) to reuse a long-lived process similar to Visual Studio, or using `dotnet watch` for the inner dev loop to avoid repeated startup overhead.\n\nThe most impactful fix is enabling the MSBuild Build Server with the environment variable, which eliminates the process startup penalty between builds. The key optimizations are enabling the Roslyn compiler server through shared compilation to avoid recompiling between builds, using `dotnet watch` for the development loop to keep the host alive, and skipping the restore phase on subsequent builds with `--no-restore` since NuGet overhead adds up even when there's nothing to restore.\n\nLooking at the actual bottleneck the developer reported—MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation taking most of the time—I should verify whether `UseSharedCompilation` is already enabled by default in their SDK version, since that's the primary lever for reducing startup overhead.\n\nThe real solutions are practical: using `dotnet watch build` to keep the process alive between rebuilds, adding `--no-restore` to skip unnecessary restore checks, and enabling the MSBuild Server if their SDK supports it. These are invocation-level changes rather than project file modifications, since the compilation itself is already fast at under 500ms.","outputTokens":1753,"requestId":"4412:2D7D24:C37CA2:E3787B:69FE84FC"},"id":"9a18b442-e517-4639-ac42-7c35a40cae7b","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:54.661Z","parentId":"5896645f-8c79-4e39-9b5c-75085b70cdeb"}
